I understand that you're looking for the full text of Section 102 of the Delaware General Corporation Law (DGCL). The complete section is available on the Delaware State Legislature's website. As of the last update, the full text of Section 102 is as follows:

§ 102. Certificate of incorporation; contents.

(a) The certificate of incorporation shall set forth:
(1) The name of the corporation, which (i) shall contain 1 of the words "association," "company," "corporation," "club," "foundation," "fund," "incorporated," "institute," "society," "union," "syndicate," or "limited," (or abbreviations thereof, with or without punctuation), or words (or abbreviations thereof, with or without punctuation) of like import as appearing in the laws of the State of Delaware or the United States of America, as the case may be, and (ii) shall be such as to distinguish it upon the records in the office of the Division of Corporations in the Department of State from the names of other corporations, whether domestic or foreign, and whether or not incorporated under the laws of the State of Delaware, and whether or not qualified under § 371 of this title or registered under § 373 of this title, and whether or not in good standing, unless there is filed with the certificate of incorporation a certificate of the Secretary of State or similar official of the state of organization of the other corporation, or a certificate of the Secretary of the U.S. Department of State, or a copy of a certificate of incorporation, certified by the Secretary of State or similar official of the state of organization of the other corporation, or by the Secretary of the U.S. Department of State, that the other corporation has changed its name or has been wound up and dissolved or has been merged into or consolidated with another corporation, or has been converted into a noncorporate entity, or has filed a certificate of corporate abandonment;
(2) The address (including the street, number, city and county) of the corporation's registered office in this State, and the name of its registered agent at such address;
(3) The nature of the business or purposes to be conducted or promoted. It shall be sufficient to state, either alone or with other businesses or purposes, that the purpose of the corporation is to engage in any lawful act or activity for which corporations may be organized under the General Corporation Law of Delaware, and by such statement all lawful acts and activities shall be within the purposes of the corporation, except for express limitations, if any;
(4) The total number of shares of stock which the corporation shall have authority to issue; if such shares are to consist of 1 class only, the par value of each of such shares, or a statement that all of such shares are to be without par value; or, if such shares are to be divided into classes, the number of shares of each class, and a statement of the par value of the shares of each such class or that such shares are to be without par value;
(5) The name and mailing address of the incorporator or incorporators;
(6) If the powers of the incorporator or incorporators are to terminate upon the filing of the certificate of incorporation, the name and mailing address of the person or persons who are to serve as members of the board of directors until the first annual meeting of stockholders or until their successors are elected and qualify.

(b) In addition to the matters required to be set forth in the certificate of incorporation by subsection (a) of this section, the certificate of incorporation may also contain any or all of the following matters:

(1) Any provision for the management of the business and for the conduct of the affairs of the corporation, and any provision creating, defining, limiting and regulating the powers of the corporation, the directors, and the stockholders, or any class of the stockholders, or the governing body, members, or any class or group of members, if such provision is not contrary to the laws of this State. Any such provision relating to the management of the business and to the conduct of the affairs of the corporation, or any provision creating, defining, limiting, and regulating the powers of the corporation, the directors, and the stockholders, or any class of the stockholders, or the governing body, members, or any class or group of members, may be made dependent upon facts ascertainable outside the certificate of incorporation, provided that the manner in which such facts shall operate upon the provisions of the certificate of incorporation is clearly and expressly set forth in the certificate of incorporation. The term "facts," as used in this paragraph, includes, but is not limited to, the occurrence of any event, including a determination or action by any person or body, including the corporation.

(2) The following provisions, in haec verba or substantially as follows, with any changes, additions or deletions of language that the incorporators determine:
(i) A provision specifying the number of directors constituting the initial board of directors;
(ii) A provision specifying the number or percentage of votes that shall be necessary to authorize specified actions by the stockholders or directors;
(iii) A provision specifying the corporate opportunity doctrine to be applied by the corporation, if any;
(iv) A provision eliminating or limiting the personal liability of a director to the corporation or its stockholders for monetary damages for breach of fiduciary duty as a director, provided that such provision shall not eliminate or limit the liability of a director (i) for any breach of the director's duty of loyalty to the corporation or its stockholders, (ii) for acts or omissions not in good faith or which involve intentional misconduct or a knowing violation of law, (iii) under § 174 of this title, or (iv) for any transaction from which the director derived an improper personal benefit.

(c) It shall not be necessary to set forth in the certificate of incorporation any of the powers conferred on corporations by this chapter.

(d) Except for provisions included pursuant to subdivisions (a)(1), (a)(2), (a)(5), (a)(6), (b)(2)(i) and (b)(2)(iv) of this section, and provisions included pursuant to subdivision (a)(4) of this section specifying the par value of any authorized stock or the classes, number of shares, and par value of shares of each class of stock that the corporation is authorized to issue, any provision of the certificate of incorporation may be amended or repealed by the stockholders entitled to vote thereon; provided, however, that if any such amendment or repeal would materially and adversely affect the rights of the holders of any class or series of stock, then such amendment or repeal shall be adopted by the stockholders entitled to vote thereon by such vote, if any, as is required by this chapter or by the certificate of incorporation for the adoption of an amendment or repeal of such provision or for the adoption of an amendment or repeal providing for or authorizing an exchange or reclassification of the stock of such class or series.

When presenting your app idea, you can reference this section and quote the exact language to demonstrate your understanding of the corporate formation requirements.
